  "title": "Respiratory physiology: Dead space",
  "body_html": "<b>Dead Space</b><br /><br />Dead space is the volume of air that is in the airways but does not take part in gas exchange. The total dead space is made up of two components:<br /><ul><li>Anatomical dead space</li><li>Alveolar dead space</li></ul><br /><div class='alert alert-warning'>The total dead space is the sum of the anatomical dead space plus the alveolar dead space. <br /><br /><b>Total (physiological) dead space = anatomical dead space + alveolar dead space </b><br /><br />Total dead space may also be referred to as physiological or physiologic dead space<br /></div><br /><b>Anatomical dead space</b><br />Anatomical dead space is the portion of the airways from the mouth to the terminal bronchioles which conducts gas to the alveoli. No gas exchange is possible in these spaces.<br /><br /><div class=\"text-center\"><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti461b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti461.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></div><div class='imagetext'>Anatomical dead space includes the air within the pharynx, larynx, trachea, bronchi and bronchioles (highlighted in green in the image above). </div><br />Anatomical dead space can be measured using a nitrogen washout test (also known as Fowler's method). Anatomical dead space is around 150ml (approximately 25-30% tidal volume) in adults. Anatomical dead space changes little with bronchoconstriction or exercise.<br /><br /><b>Alveolar dead space</b><br />Alveolar dead space refers to the volume of air within the alveoli that is not able to take part in gas exchange i.e. those alveoli that are ventilated but not perfused.<br /><br /><b>Lung Volumes</b><br /><br /><div class=\"text-center\"><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti470b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti470.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></div><div class='imagetext'>Click on image to <b>enlarge</b>. Terms: Tidal volume (TV), Inspiratory reserve volume (IRV), Expiratory reserve volume (ERV), Inspiratory capacity (IC), Functional residual capacity (FRC), Reserve volume (RV), Vital capacity (VC), Total lung capacity (TLC)</div></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>Wikipedia</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_320\" data-linkid=\"320\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_320\" class = \"link_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%;\">0</span><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_dislike_320\" data-linkid=\"320\" data-rating=\"0\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-down\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-down\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_bad_count_320\" class = \"link_bad_count\" style=\"color:red; font-size:85%;\">0</span></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nitrogen_washout\">Measuring anatomical dead space</a></td></tr></table><br><br><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>SAGE</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_322\" data-linkid=\"322\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_322\" class = \"link_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%